Experiment 3: Modelling with and without causality (non-linear problem)¶

The goal of this experiment is to check if having causality information of the variables of our data set is useful to improve our models.

The experiment has the following steps:

  1. Define a causal graph (Directed Acyclic graph) relating five (5) hypothetical variables. Some of them will be supposed to be unknown.
  2. Define causal rules between those variables
  3. Generate a data set following the rules
  4. Train a general ML model on the data set in order to predict the effect of X into Y
  5. Train a general ML model on the data set using the causal information in order to predict the effect of X into Y.
  6. Compare the performance of the two approaches:
    1. On unseen data that follows the distribution of the training set
    2. On unseen data that does not follow the distribution of the training set

1. Define a causal graph¶

Here I define a causal graph whose relations may cause problems if not adequately treated. Nodes in gray will not be visible in the dataset.

The problem presented to the ML practitioner will be:

Can you estimate the real influence of X in Y?
I mean, what happens to Y when I increase X by one unit, keeping all the same equal?

Let's define some rules to later generate a data set:

SensorActivado[np.logical_and(Conduc <= 40, NivelAgua <= 20)] = 0

In [162]:



    


from sklearn.tree import _tree

def tree_to_code(tree, feature_names):
    tree_ = tree.tree_
    feature_name = [
        feature_names[i] if i != _tree.TREE_UNDEFINED else "undefined!"
        for i in tree_.feature
    ]
    print("def tree({}):".format(", ".join(feature_names)))

    def recurse(node, depth):
        indent = "  " * depth
        if tree_.feature[node] != _tree.TREE_UNDEFINED:
            name = feature_name[node]
            threshold = tree_.threshold[node]
            print("{}if {} <= {}:".format(indent, name, threshold))
            recurse(tree_.children_left[node], depth + 1)
            print("{}else:  # if {} > {}".format(indent, name, threshold))
            recurse(tree_.children_right[node], depth + 1)
        else:
            print("{}return {}".format(indent, tree_.value[node]))

    recurse(0, 1)



    













In [163]:



    


tree_to_code(dt, ['Arcoiris', 'NivelAgua'])



    















    






def tree(Arcoiris, NivelAgua):
  if Arcoiris <= 0.5:
    if NivelAgua <= 10.8264479637146:
      return [[0.82238935]]
    else:  # if NivelAgua > 10.8264479637146
      return [[0.13333333]]
  else:  # if Arcoiris > 0.5
    return [[1.]]





















El modelo dice que que el corte en NivelAgua está en 10.82, y que a mayor NivelAgua, menor SensorActivado.


¡La relación capturada con el modelo no tiene nada que ver con la realidad! (si NivelAgua > 20 => SensorActivado = 1)















5. Train a general ML model using causal information¶
Looking at the causal graph, it is clear that, in order to get the isolated influence of NivelAgua we need to ignore Arcoiris, as considering it will open the collider path and create a counfounding situation.


So let's try the same model, but training only on NivelAgua:













In [164]:



    


X_train_causal = X_train[['NivelAgua']]
X_test_causal = X_test[['NivelAgua']]



    













In [177]:



    


causal_dt = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=1)
causal_dt.fit(X_train_causal, y_train)
predictions_causal_dt = causal_dt.predict(X_test_causal) > .5
print("Acc in Test set = {}".format(np.round(accuracy_score(predictions_causal_dt, y_test), decimals=2)))



    















    






Acc in Test set = 0.84





















The model is quite worse when predicting SensorActivado (as expected; it is only considering the influence of NivelAgua). It is in fact predicting SensorActivado = 1 for every sample:













In [178]:



    


np.sum(predictions_causal_dt) / len(predictions_causal_dt)



    















    
Out[178]:








1.0





















But let's see what patterns the model has captured:













In [175]:



    


tree_to_code(causal_dt, ['NivelAgua'])



    















    






def tree(NivelAgua):
  if NivelAgua <= 19.95685386657715:
    return [[0.84139549]]
  else:  # if NivelAgua > 19.95685386657715
    return [[1.]]





















The model says that when NivelAgua > 19.98, SensorActivado = 1. And that when NivelAgua < 19.98, SensorActivado = 0.84. This is exactly what is happening!


If NivelAgua > 20, and whatever value Conduc has, SensorActivado = 1.
If NivelAgua < 20, the value of SensorActivado depends totally on the value of Conduc, and probably 84% of those samples have a Conduc value that activates SensorActivado:

np.sum(X_test.loc[X_test.NivelAgua < 20]['Conduc'] > 40) / X_test.shape[0]



    















    
Out[182]:








0.8163333333333334





















Almost as predicted!!















Now, let's see if the theory works. If I train with NivelAgua and Conduc, the model should be able to capture the underlying patters without bias:

It is able to perfectly predict the test set!!













In [186]:



    


tree_to_code(causal_dt2, ['NivelAgua', 'Conduc'])



    















    






def tree(NivelAgua, Conduc):
  if Conduc <= 39.99171447753906:
    if NivelAgua <= 20.04405975341797:
      return [[0.]]
    else:  # if NivelAgua > 20.04405975341797
      return [[1.]]
  else:  # if Conduc > 39.99171447753906
    return [[1.]]





















Incredible! The model has captured the exact underlying relationship between the three features!

Again, the causal inference method performs much better!

This is not surprising after seeing the estimation of coefficients made by each method.















Conclusion¶
    

  • Decisions of feature selection based on causal knowledge are useful for non-linear models too. Interactions are different and model-dependent, but when they occur in a particular order, they are prone to capture spurious correlations if we do not select the appropiate features.
    

    • 

  • Modelling with the correct variables helps the model capture the true underlying causal relationships.
